1
00:00:01,890 --> 00:00:05,922
Back in the first course,
you have seen how for linear regression,

2
00:00:05,922 --> 00:00:09,410
future normalization can help
the algorithm run faster.

3
00:00:09,410 --> 00:00:12,140
In the case of building
a recommended system

4
00:00:12,140 --> 00:00:15,680
with numbers wide such as movie
ratings from one to five or

5
00:00:15,680 --> 00:00:20,425
zero to five stars, it turns out your
algorithm will run more efficiently.

6
00:00:20,425 --> 00:00:25,490
And also perform a bit better if you
first carry out mean normalization.

7
00:00:25,490 --> 00:00:30,978
That is if you normalize the movie ratings
to have a consistent average value,

8
00:00:30,978 --> 00:00:33,660
let's take a look at what that means.

9
00:00:33,660 --> 00:00:36,540
So here's the data set
that we've been using.

10
00:00:36,540 --> 00:00:41,699
And down below is the cost function
you used to learn the parameters for

11
00:00:41,699 --> 00:00:42,590
the model.

12
00:00:42,590 --> 00:00:46,638
In order to explain mean normalization,

13
00:00:46,638 --> 00:00:53,480
Im ctually going to add fifth user
Eve who has not yet rated any movies.

14
00:00:53,480 --> 00:00:58,237
And you see in a little bit that
adding mean normalization will

15
00:00:58,237 --> 00:01:02,930
help the algorithm make better
predictions on the user Eve.

16
00:01:02,930 --> 00:01:07,771
In fact, if you were to train
a collaborative filtering algorithm

17
00:01:07,771 --> 00:01:12,440
on this data, then because we
are trying to make the parameters w

18
00:01:12,440 --> 00:01:15,733
small because of this regularization term.

19
00:01:15,733 --> 00:01:20,386
If you were to run
the algorithm on this dataset,

20
00:01:20,386 --> 00:01:26,174
you actually end up with
the parameters w for the fifth user,

21
00:01:26,174 --> 00:01:33,464
for the user Eve to be equal to [0
0] as well as quite likely b(5) = 0.

22
00:01:33,464 --> 00:01:38,260
Because Eve hasn't rated any movies yet,
the parameters w and

23
00:01:38,260 --> 00:01:43,329
b don't affect this first term in
the cost function because none of

24
00:01:43,329 --> 00:01:48,880
Eve's movie's rating play a role in
this squared error cost function.

25
00:01:48,880 --> 00:01:55,520
And so minimizing this means making
the parameters w as small as possible.

26
00:01:55,520 --> 00:01:57,221
We didn't really regularize b.

27
00:01:57,221 --> 00:02:03,850
But if you initialize b to 0 as the
default, you end up with b(%) = 0 as well.

28
00:02:03,850 --> 00:02:09,333
But if these are the parameters for
user 5 that is for

29
00:02:09,333 --> 00:02:15,065
Eve, then what the average
will end up doing is predict

30
00:02:15,065 --> 00:02:23,070
that all of Eve's movies ratings
with be w(%).x for movie i + b(5).

31
00:02:23,070 --> 00:02:27,000
And this is equal to 0 if w and
b above equals 0.

32
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:31,265
And so this algorithm will predict that
if you have a new user that has not yet

33
00:02:31,265 --> 00:02:35,258
rated anything, we think they'll
rate all movies with zero stars and

34
00:02:35,258 --> 00:02:37,900
that's not particularly hopeful.

35
00:02:37,900 --> 00:02:42,561
So in this video, we'll see that
mean normalization will help this

36
00:02:42,561 --> 00:02:47,142
algorithm come up with better
predictions of the movie ratings for

37
00:02:47,142 --> 00:02:50,360
a new user that has not yet
rated any movies.

38
00:02:50,360 --> 00:02:53,566
In order to describe mean normalization,

39
00:02:53,566 --> 00:02:58,730
let me take all of the values here
including all the question marks for

40
00:02:58,730 --> 00:03:02,841
Eve and put them in a two
dimensional matrix like this.

41
00:03:02,841 --> 00:03:07,368
Just to write out all the ratings
including the question marks in a more

42
00:03:07,368 --> 00:03:09,528
sustained and more compact way.

43
00:03:09,528 --> 00:03:12,248
To carry out mean normalization,

44
00:03:12,248 --> 00:03:16,747
what we're going to do is take
all of these ratings and for

45
00:03:16,747 --> 00:03:21,280
each movie,
compute the average rating that was given.

46
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:26,830
So movie one had two 5s and two 0s and
so the average rating is 2.5.

47
00:03:26,830 --> 00:03:31,410
Movie two had a 5 and a 0,
so that averages out to 2.5.

48
00:03:31,410 --> 00:03:34,400
Movie three 4 and 0 averages out to 2.

49
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:38,810
Movie four averages out to 2.25 rating.

50
00:03:38,810 --> 00:03:45,100
And movie five not that popular,
has an average 1.25 rating.

51
00:03:45,100 --> 00:03:47,891
So I'm going to take all
of these five numbers and

52
00:03:47,891 --> 00:03:52,328
gather them into a vector which I'm
going to call μ because this is the vector

53
00:03:52,328 --> 00:03:55,421
of the average ratings that
each of the movies had.

54
00:03:55,421 --> 00:03:59,437
Averaging over just the users that
did read that particular movie.

55
00:03:59,437 --> 00:04:04,599
Instead of using these original 0
to 5 star ratings over here, I'm

56
00:04:04,599 --> 00:04:10,834
going to take this and subtract from every
rating the mean rating that it was given.

57
00:04:10,834 --> 00:04:15,610
So for example this movie rating was 5.

58
00:04:15,610 --> 00:04:20,519
I'm going to subtract 2.5
giving me 2.5 over here.

59
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:23,031
This movie had a 0 star rating.

60
00:04:23,031 --> 00:04:29,158
I'm going to subtract 2.25 giving
me a -2.25 rating and so on for all

61
00:04:29,158 --> 00:04:35,500
of the now five users including the new
user Eve as well as for all five movies.

62
00:04:35,500 --> 00:04:39,870
Then these new values on the right
become your new values of Y(i,j).

63
00:04:39,870 --> 00:04:45,372
We're going to pretend that user 1 had
given a 2.5 rating to movie one and

64
00:04:45,372 --> 00:04:48,230
the -2.25 rating to movie four.

65
00:04:48,230 --> 00:04:53,119
And using this, you can then learn w(j),

66
00:04:53,119 --> 00:04:59,065
b(j) and x(i) same as before for
user j on movie i,

67
00:04:59,065 --> 00:05:04,830
you would predict w(j).x(i) + b(j).

68
00:05:04,830 --> 00:05:09,891
But because we had subtracted off µi for
movie i during this mean

69
00:05:09,891 --> 00:05:14,764
normalization step,
in order to predict not a negative star

70
00:05:14,764 --> 00:05:19,760
rating which is impossible for
user rates from 0 to 5 stars.

71
00:05:19,760 --> 00:05:26,000
We have to add back this µi which is
just the value we have subtracted out.

72
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:31,024
So as a concrete example,
if we look at what happens with user

73
00:05:31,024 --> 00:05:36,340
5 with the new user Eve because
she had not yet rated any movies,

74
00:05:36,340 --> 00:05:42,870
the average might learn parameters
w(5) = [0 0] and say b(5) = 0.

75
00:05:42,870 --> 00:05:48,548
And so
if we look at the predicted rating for

76
00:05:48,548 --> 00:05:53,911
movie one, we will predict that Eve will

77
00:05:53,911 --> 00:06:00,378
rate it w(5).x1 + b(5) but this is 0 and

78
00:06:00,378 --> 00:06:05,300
then + µ1 which is equal to 2.5.

79
00:06:05,300 --> 00:06:09,883
So this seems more reasonable to think
Eve is likely to rate this movie

80
00:06:09,883 --> 00:06:14,860
2.5 rather than think Eve will rate
all movie zero stars just because she

81
00:06:14,860 --> 00:06:16,940
hasn't rated any movies yet.

82
00:06:16,940 --> 00:06:21,390
And in fact the effect of this
algorithm is it will cause

83
00:06:21,390 --> 00:06:26,033
the initial guesses for
the new user Eve to be just equal to

84
00:06:26,033 --> 00:06:31,200
the mean of whatever other users
have rated these five movies.

85
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:35,921
And that seems more reasonable to
take the average rating of the movies

86
00:06:35,921 --> 00:06:40,020
rather than to guess that all
the ratings by Eve will be zero.

87
00:06:40,020 --> 00:06:44,937
It turns out that by normalizing
the mean of the different movies ratings

88
00:06:44,937 --> 00:06:47,920
to be zero, the optimization algorithm for

89
00:06:47,920 --> 00:06:52,210
the recommended system will also
run just a little bit faster.

90
00:06:52,210 --> 00:06:55,818
But it does make the algorithm
behave much better for

91
00:06:55,818 --> 00:07:00,180
users who have rated no movies or
very small numbers of movies.

92
00:07:00,180 --> 00:07:04,040
And the predictions will
become more reasonable.

93
00:07:04,040 --> 00:07:05,100
In this example,

94
00:07:05,100 --> 00:07:09,555
what we did was normalize each of the rows
of this matrix to have zero mean and

95
00:07:09,555 --> 00:07:14,900
we saw this helps when there's a new user
that hasn't rated a lot of movies yet.

96
00:07:14,900 --> 00:07:19,873
There's one other alternative that
you could use which is to instead

97
00:07:19,873 --> 00:07:23,920
normalize the columns of this
matrix to have zero mean.

98
00:07:23,920 --> 00:07:26,620
And that would be
a reasonable thing to do too.

99
00:07:26,620 --> 00:07:30,915
But I think in this application,
normalizing the rows so

100
00:07:30,915 --> 00:07:33,956
that you can give reasonable ratings for

101
00:07:33,956 --> 00:07:39,270
a new user seems more important
than normalizing the columns.

102
00:07:39,270 --> 00:07:43,765
Normalizing the columns would hope if
there was a brand new movie that no one

103
00:07:43,765 --> 00:07:44,710
has rated yet.

104
00:07:44,710 --> 00:07:48,151
But if there's a brand new movie
that no one has rated yet,

105
00:07:48,151 --> 00:07:52,859
you probably shouldn't show that movie
to too many users initially because you

106
00:07:52,859 --> 00:07:55,530
don't know that much about that movie.

107
00:07:55,530 --> 00:08:00,445
So normalizing columns the hope with
the case of a movie with no ratings

108
00:08:00,445 --> 00:08:04,194
seems less important to me
than normalizing the rules

109
00:08:04,194 --> 00:08:09,140
to hope with the case of a new user
that's hardly rated any movies yet.

110
00:08:09,140 --> 00:08:13,469
And when you are building your own
recommended system in this week's

111
00:08:13,469 --> 00:08:17,530
practice lab, normalizing just
the roles should work fine.

112
00:08:17,530 --> 00:08:19,730
So that's mean normalization.

113
00:08:19,730 --> 00:08:22,050
It makes the algorithm
run a little bit faster.

114
00:08:22,050 --> 00:08:26,544
But even more important, it makes
the algorithm give much better, much

115
00:08:26,544 --> 00:08:31,407
more reasonable predictions when there
are users that rated very few movies or

116
00:08:31,407 --> 00:08:32,820
even no movies at all.

117
00:08:32,820 --> 00:08:37,324
This implementation detail of mean
normalization will make your recommended

118
00:08:37,324 --> 00:08:39,630
system work much better.

119
00:08:39,630 --> 00:08:43,864
Next, let's go into the next video to
talk about how you can implement this for

120
00:08:43,864 --> 00:08:45,351
